<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-806-662  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 806 662.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 3 1990 v9 n18 p3(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army to test Desktop II, III compatibility. (Computer EngineeringCommand to test interconnectivity of hardware and softwarecomponents of two contracts)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taft, Darryl K.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Hardware SelectionSoftware SelectionPurchasing SystemsDefense ContractsUnited States. Army. Computer Engineering CommandTestingCompatibilityUnited States. Air ForceInteroperabilityPeripherals.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Army to Test Desktop II, III CompatibilityandM;The Army's Computer Engineering Command (CEC) at Fort Huachuca, Ariz., willrun a series of tests to determine the extent of compatibility betweencomponents on the Air Force Desktop III contract and hardware and softwaefrom the preceding Desktop II contract, CEC officials said last week.andM;Although the Army would give few details, some sources said the Air Forceasked the Army to undertake the testing.andP;  Army spokeswoman Kathleen B.andO;Whitaker said, &quot;The Air Force is the lead service on the Desktop IIIcontract.andP;  The Army will coordinate activities with the Air Force throughoutthe lie of the contract.&quot;andM;CEC officials said they were not aware of any other organization inside oroutside the Army planning to do any formal evaluations of Desktop IIIequipment for Desktop II compatibility.andP;  CEC officials simply acknowledgedthey would be conducting compatibility tests and that &quot;the evaluations willconsist of hardware and software from the Desktop III and Desktop IIcontracts.&quot;andM;&quot;The purpose of the evaluation is to determine component interoperability,&quot;said Whitaker, a public affairs official with the Army Information SystemsEngineering Command at Fort Huachuca, CEC's parent organization.andP;  She saidthe center still was preparing its order for Desktop III equipment.andM;Also, with testing yet to begin, the Army has not developed a timetable forthe project.andM;CEC officials said it would be difficult to put a time frame on the testingbecause of other considerations.andP;  &quot;The workload and project priority at theCEC is ever-changing.andP;  There is always the possibility of a higher-priorityproject being received that would delay any evaluations on the Desktop IIIequipment,&quot; Whitaker said.andM;CEC officials would not comment on what components would betested, but theyare likely to include such items as VGA cars, drive controllers, monitors andprinters.andP;  Army officials said CEC will report its testing results to Armyand Air Force small computer program managers.andM;The Army's compatibility tests and any resulting report also will not includeany findings or recommendations on Desktop III warranty issues, Whitakersaid.andM;The Desktop III warranty has been a sticking pointwith many users hoping touse new components in their existing hardware.andP;  Unisys Corp. has said thatthe two-year warranty on Desktop III equipment becomes invalid if thecomponents are used in other computers.andO;</TEXT></DOC>